w range amid uncertainty over the Middle East conflict. | April 20, 69](https://en.moneyandbanking.co.th/2026/238990/)\n\n![](https://moneyandbanking.co.th/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/%E0%B8%9B%E0%B8%81%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%A7%E0%B9%87%E0%B8%9A-17-04-69-90x65.jpg)\n\n#### [Iran's cunning war plan! When \"Low-tech\" slaps \"High-tech\" in the face | April 17, 69](https://en.moneyandbanking.co.th/2026/238978/)\n\n![](https://moneyandbanking.co.th/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B9%E0%B8%9B%E0%B8%AB%E0%B8%99%E0%B9%89%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%9B%E0%B8%81-website-8-90x65.jpg)\n\n#### [The oil crisis is far from over. What should we do with oil and petrochemical stocks? | Market Today](https://en.moneyandbanking.co.th/2026/238588/)"}, {"url": "https://www.undp.org/sites/g/files/zskgke326/files/2025-01/irff-roadmap_en_22122024.pdf", "title": "[PDF] INSURANCE AND RISK FINANCE FOR THAILAND: A ROADMAP", "content": "20 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 Figure 2 Life and Non-Life Insurance Penetration (%) from 2013-2020 Thailand has developed various frameworks and strategies aimed at enhancing its resilience to natural disasters and climate risks. 35 Strategic Interventions and Initiatives 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 In parallel strengthening regulatory capacity with the help of Office of Insurance Commission (OIC) to oversee the development and implementation of climate and disaster risk insurance, ensuring transparency, equity, and financial stability within the insurance market. PHASE 3: CONSOLIDATION (2025 - 2030) The consolidation phase of the roadmap will see the integration of inclusive insurance and risk financing solutions into Thailand’s long-term national development and disaster risk management strategies. • Evaluate whether the strategy has improved Thailand’s financial resilience against climate-related risks and disasters, and whether new insurance products have been successfully integrated into the market.", "score": 0.5553635, "raw_content": "INSURANCE AND RISK FINANCE FOR THAILAND: A ROADMAP Insurance and Risk Finance Facility December 2024 UNDP Thailand UNDP partners with people at all levels of society to help build nations that can withstand crisis, and drive and sustain the kind of growth that improves the quality of life for everyone. On the ground in more than 170 countries and territories, we offer global perspective and local insight to help empower lives and build resilient nations.\nThe findings, interpretations and conclusions expressed herein are entirely those of the author(s) and do not necessarily reflect the view of UNDP. UNDP cannot guarantee the accuracy of the data included in this work. The boundaries, colours, denominations and other information shown on any map in this work do not imply on the part of UNDP any judgement of the legal status of any territory or the endorsement or acceptance of such boundaries.\nCopyright © UNDP 2024 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap United Nations Development Programme Thailand 14th Floor United Nations Building Rajdamnern Nok Avenue Bangkok 10200, Thailand Email: undp.thailand@undp.org http://www.th.undp.org UNDPThailand Tel: +66 2 288 3350 INSURANCE AND RISK FINANCE FOR THAILAND: A ROADMAP December 2024 UNDP Thailand Insurance and Risk Finance Facility TABLE OF CONTENTS 1. Introduction and Background 6 2. Objectives and Scope 10 3. Insurance and Risk Finance Mechanisms 12 4. Thailand’s Insurance and Risk Financing Landscape 18 4.1. Thailand Insurance Market 22 4.2. Socio-Economic Factors Influencing Insurance Demand 24 and Risk Financing Needs 4.3. Environmental Factors Influencing Insurance Demand 25 and Risk Financing Needs 4.4. Social Vulnerability and Insurance Accessibility 26 4.5. Key Gaps in Current Mechanisms 27 4.6. Opportunities for Strengthening Insurance 29 and Risk Financing in Thailand 5. Strategic Interventions and Initiatives 32 5.1. Development of a National Strategy / Frameworks 33 5.2. Establishment of Comprehensive Risk Analytics 33 5.3. Development of Inclusive Insurance Products 33 5.4. Strengthening Public-Private Partnerships (PPP) 34 5.5. Institutional Strengthening and Market Development 34 5.6. Development of Innovative Financing Instruments 35 6. Phased Approach of Roadmap 36 6.1. Phase 1: Foundation (2024 - 2025) 37 6.2. Phase 2: Development (2025 - 2027) 37 6.3. Phase 3: Consolidation (2025 - 2030) 38 7. Monitoring and Evaluation (M&E) Framework for the Roadmap 43 7.1. Baseline Data Collection 44 7.2. Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) 44 7.3. Semi-Annual or Annual Review 45 7.4. Mid-Term Evaluation 46 7.5. Long-Term Impact Assessment 46 8. References 48 6 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 INTRODUCTION AND BACKGROUND 01 Insurance and risk finance has gained significant attention as a critical component for building resilience against risks linked with climate change and several other natural hazards. It aims to provide financial protection to the marginalized and vulnerable population, households, businesses, and governments by ensuring that funds are available to cover the impacts of various extremes.\nInsurance plays a pivotal role in building financial resilience by providing tailored solutions that cater to underserved segments of the population. In Thailand, significant gaps exist in coverage for those most vulnerable to disasters, particularly in rural and low-income communities. These groups face heightened exposure to climate risks yet have limited access to financial protection due to affordability, lack of financial literacy, and geographical constraints. Insurance, particularly, inclusive insurance products— such as microinsurance and weather-based insurance—are specifically designed to overcome these barriers by offering affordable premiums, simplified claims processes, and innovative distribution channels. For instance, parametric insurance, which triggers payouts based on pre-defined parameters like rainfall levels, could provide much-needed financial security to smallholder farmers facing crop losses due to erratic weather patterns.\nClimate change is having profound effects on the insurance markets globally, and Thailand is no exception. Rising temperatures, increased frequency of extreme weather events, and changing precipitation patterns are intensifying climate risks, making it critical to assess their implications for insurance and risk financing. The review of scientific literature and industry reports highlights several key trends that are reshaping the demand for insurance products and influencing the design of risk financing solutions in Thailand.\n7 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 Introduction and Background 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Firstly, the increased frequency and severity of extreme weather events—such as floods, droughts, and storms—have led to higher claims and significant financial losses for insurers. According to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), the Asia-Pacific region, including Thailand, is one of the most vulnerable to climate change impacts, with extreme weather events becoming more common (IPCC, 2021). In Thailand, the devastating floods of 2011 serve as a critical example, resulting in economic losses exceeding $45 billion and prompting a reevaluation of the country’s insurance landscape. These events have exposed the inadequacy of traditional insurance products, leading to an increased demand for innovative solutions such as parametric insurance, which provides quicker payouts based on predefined triggers (Swiss Re, 2022).\nSecondly, climate change is influencing the pricing and availability of insurance coverage. As the risks associated with climate change intensify, insurers are facing challenges in accurately pricing policies. The heightened uncertainty has led to increased premiums and, in some cases, reduced availability of coverage, particularly for high-risk areas prone to floods and tropical storms (Munich Re, 2023). This trend is evident in Thailand, where insurers have had to recalibrate their risk models, incorporating climate projections and new data on weather patterns. The adaptation of these models is crucial for sustaining the market and ensuring the availability of affordable insurance products.\nPrior to the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020, which caused a precipitous 6.2% economic contraction, Thailand had not seen a significant economic crisis since the 1997 financial crisis. Due to the permanent closure of businesses and the ensuing layoffs, unemployed people were forced into the unorganized sector, where they had fewer options for insurance protection. While advancing the nation’s development agenda and the SDGs, inclusive insurance and risk finance have enormous potential to help strengthen Thailand’s resilience against an increasing number of disasters. For the underprivileged (such as the impoverished and vulnerable community groups, farmers, and micro, small, and medium-sized businesses (MSMEs), inclusive insurance offers access to and utilization of suitable and reasonably priced insurance products. Health insurance, personal accident insurance, simple asset insurance, life insurance, and credit-linked insurance are just a few of the many products that can be covered by inclusive insurance.\nThailand has historically relied heavily on risk retention mechanisms, such as government budgets and contingency funds, to manage disaster risks. This approach has been primarily focused on providing immediate response and rehabilitation, with limited use of risk transfer instruments like insurance. The government’s reliance on internal resources, including local and central government budgets, has been the dominant strategy for financing disaster response. The country’s contingency fund, which constitutes a small percentage of the annual budget, is designed to provide advance funds for emergency relief but has become less effective over time as agencies increasingly dip into the central budget for larger expenses.\nHowever, there is a growing recognition of the need to shift toward more innovative risk finance mechanisms that integrate insurance and other financial tools. This shift could improve the country’s resilience by offering more sustainable and scalable disaster financing solutions. For instance, integrating risk transfer instruments such as insurance into ex-ante financing, funding for preparedness and mitigation before a disaster strikes, has been identified as a key opportunity. The use of insurance and other financial instruments could supplement Thailand’s reliance on public funds, thereby reducing the fiscal burden on government budgets while 8 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 enhancing the speed and efficiency of disaster recovery efforts. The inclusion of insurance schemes for public assets, as well as the potential expansion of micro-insurance and inclusive risk finance products, could also improve the financial protection of vulnerable populations.\nThe shift in demand towards climate-responsive insurance products is another emerging trend. As awareness of climate risks grows, both individuals and businesses are increasingly seeking insurance products that offer specific protection against climate-related events. In Thailand, there is a noticeable shift towards crop insurance and flood insurance, particularly in the agricultural sector, which is highly susceptible to climate impacts. Industry reports indicate a rising interest in microinsurance products as well, tailored for low-income populations who are disproportionately affected by climate shocks (Allianz, 2022). These products are designed to provide targeted coverage at affordable rates, helping to build financial resilience among vulnerable groups.\nFurthermore, the review points to the growing role of technology and data analytics in responding to climate change impacts on insurance markets. The use of big data, satellite imagery, and climate models has improved the accuracy of risk assessments, enabling insurers to better understand exposure levels and design more effective risk transfer products. In Thailand, advancements in technology are being leveraged to develop parametric insurance solutions and enhance early warning systems, which are integral to minimizing losses and improving response times (UNEP FI, 2023).\nIn short, the impacts of climate change on Thailand’s insurance market are profound, necessitating a shift towards more adaptive and innovative risk financing solutions. By incorporating climate data into risk assessments and developing new products that address emerging risks, the insurance industry can play a pivotal role in enhancing financial resilience against climate change. Effective risk financing is, therefore, critical for Thailand to ensure it can manage the financial impact of disasters without heavily burdening its public finances. Risk financing mechanisms provide a blend of pre-arranged funding and risk transfer tools, such as insurance, contingent credit, and catastrophe bonds, to address the financial needs arising from disaster events. By expanding access to such instruments, Thailand can reduce the economic shocks of disasters and build greater resilience across sectors.\nA Public Park Near the Khok River was Damaged by Typhoon Yagi, 2024 Motorbike Riding Through the Rain Storm in Koh Tao, Thailand, 2018 10 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 OBJECTIVES AND SCOPE 02 The development of a Roadmap for Insurance and Risk Finance in Thailand stems from the recognition of gaps in the country’s existing legal and policy frameworks regarding disaster risk management and financing. While Thailand has made strides in disaster management through its Disaster Prevention and Mitigation Act 2007 (DPM Act) and the National Disaster Risk Management Plan (2021-2027), there has been little integration of insurance and risk financing into these frameworks. The roadmap aims to build on Thailand’s progress in disaster risk management by incorporating inclusive insurance and risk finance into the country’s disaster resilience strategies.\nThis initiative is also expected to further the efforts of the UNDP’s work on Insurance and Risk Finance in Thailand, through the Insurance and Risk Finance Facility (IRFF). In Thailand, the UNDP has worked closely with the government and private sector stakeholders to identify and integrate insurance and risk finance solutions into the national strategy for resilience-building.\n11 Objective and Scope 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 The key objectives of the roadmap include: i. Integrating insurance and risk financing into Thailand’s existing disaster risk management frameworks to mitigate the financial impacts of disasters, especially for vulnerable populations.\nii. Addressing gaps in legal and regulatory frameworks to support the development and expansion of inclusive insurance markets.\niii. Supporting Thailand’s progress towards achieving the SDGs, particularly SDG 13: Climate Action and SDG 1: No Poverty, by providing financial protection against climate and disaster risks.\niv. Enhancing collaboration between the public and private sectors to facilitate the development of innovative insurance products such as microinsurance and parametric insurance.\nv. Building capacity within local institutions and communities to understand, adopt, and implement risk financing mechanisms, in line with Thailand’s national development goals, Insurance and Risk Finance Facility, and global frameworks such as the Sendai Framework for Disaster Risk Reduction, and the Paris Agreement. The roadmap development will focus on providing a structured, step-by-step approach to integrate insurance and risk finance into Thailand’s disaster management and resilience-building framework.\nA Family Navigating Through the Flooded Streets of Bangkok using Foam Boards and Paddles as Makeshift Rafts, 2011 12 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 INSURANCE AND RISK FINANCE MECHANISMS 03 The synthesis of findings from the literature review provides a robust foundation for developing a strategic framework for insurance and risk financing tailored to Thailand’s unique context. By integrating insights from global and regional reports, country-specific policies, and market analysis, the framework can address critical gaps, align with international best practices, and respond effectively to Thailand’s socio-economic and climate risk profile.\nFirstly, the review of global and regional reports highlights the importance of adopting innovative risk financing mechanisms, such as parametric insurance and catastrophe bonds, which have proven effective in similar socio-economic contexts across Asia. For instance, the World Bank’s Disaster Insurance and Risk Financing Program underscores the need for a diversified approach, combining risk retention, transfer mechanisms, and contingent credit facilities to build a comprehensive financial protection strategy (World Bank, 2022). This approach is particularly relevant for Thailand, where climate-induced disasters are frequent, and reliance on ad-hoc emergency funding has led to delays in response and recovery. By incorporating these best practices, the framework can promote greater financial preparedness and resilience.\nThe analysis of country-specific policies and frameworks reveals that Thailand already has a solid foundation in place, particularly with its National Disaster Risk Management Plan and National Financial Inclusion Strategy. However, there are notable gaps in integrating risk financing into broader disaster risk management (DRM) and climate adaptation strategies. While Thailand’s fiscal risk management policies provide a basis for risk assessment, there is limited emphasis on leveraging risk transfer instruments to safeguard public finances against disaster losses (ADB, 2023). The strategic framework will therefore need to enhance the linkage between financial inclusion, DRM, and climate resilience by incorporating targeted insurance solutions, especially for high-risk sectors like agriculture and infrastructure.\n13 Insurance and Risk Finance Mechanisms 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 The Snapshot on Insurance and Risk Finance and the Country Diagnostic on Inclusive Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand in 2023 by UNDP offers valuable insights into the current market landscape, highlighting significant coverage produced gaps and the need for enhanced market readiness. Despite ongoing efforts, the low penetration of inclusive insurance products remains a challenge, particularly for vulnerable communities such as smallholder farmers and informal sector workers (UNDP, 2023). The strategic framework should prioritize expanding access to inclusive insurance by fostering public-private partnerships and leveraging technological innovations, such as digital platforms and mobile-based microinsurance products. This approach can help increase awareness and uptake of insurance, bridging the existing coverage gaps.\nThe review of climate change impacts on insurance markets further emphasizes the need for adaptation and flexibility in designing risk financing solutions. As climate risks escalate, traditional insurance models are becoming increasingly inadequate, necessitating a shift towards data-driven and climate-responsive products. The framework should integrate advanced risk assessment tools, such as climate modeling and satellite imagery, to improve the accuracy of risk pricing and enhance the development of parametric insurance products tailored to Thailand’s specific climate vulnerabilities (Munich Re, 2023). By incorporating these tools, the framework can support the design of scalable and efficient insurance solutions that cater to the evolving risk landscape.\nFoundational work such as the World Bank’s Disaster Risk Financing and Insurance Program and the Asian Development Bank’s Disaster Risk Financing in Asia provide a comprehensive understanding of current practices in risk financing across diverse socio-economic contexts. These reports are pivotal in understanding the evolution of disaster risk financing mechanisms and offer strategic insights for countries like Thailand, which face similar vulnerabilities.\nThe World Bank’s Disaster Risk Financing and Insurance Program (DRFIP) highlights a range of innovative solutions designed to enhance financial resilience against disasters. The report emphasizes the integration of risk financing strategies into national disaster risk management frameworks. It showcases tools such as catastrophe bonds, parametric insurance, and contingent credit lines, demonstrating their effectiveness in providing timely liquidity post-disaster (World Bank, 2021). The program also underscores the importance of capacity building, recommending the training of government officials and stakeholders to strengthen the understanding and application of complex financial instruments. This focus on capacity development is especially relevant for Thailand, where the expertise in advanced financial solutions may need further enhancement.\nThe Asian Development Bank’s Disaster Risk Financing in Asia offers an in-depth analysis of risk financing initiatives across the region, highlighting best practices from countries like the Philippines and Indonesia. These countries have successfully implemented national catastrophe insurance pools and sovereign disaster risk insurance schemes, setting examples of robust financial preparedness (ADB, 2022). The report emphasizes the importance of regional collaboration, aligning national policies with broader frameworks like the ASEAN Disaster Risk Financing and Insurance (ADRFI) initiative. This is particularly valuable for Thailand, which stands to benefit from leveraging similar regional mechanisms to enhance its own financial preparedness against climate-induced disasters.\n14 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 Both reports advocate for a multi-layered risk financing approach, combining elements of risk retention, risk transfer, and risk pooling. This holistic strategy is crucial for countries with high exposure to natural hazards and limited fiscal capacity. Furthermore, the reports emphasize the use of data analytics and advanced risk assessment tools to improve financial planning precision and tailor solutions to a country’s specific risk profile (World Bank, 2021; ADB, 2022).\nThe emergence of regional risk financing initiatives in Southeast Asia highlights a strategic response to the escalating financial challenges posed by climate risks. Among these initiatives, the Southeast Asia Disaster Risk Insurance Facility (SEADRIF) and the ASEAN Disaster Risk Financing (DRF) frameworks stand out as pivotal efforts aimed at mitigating the economic impacts of disasters through pooled resources and regional cooperation.\nSEADRIF, established in 2016, is a collaborative effort between Southeast Asian nations and development partners, designed to offer a financial safety net during disaster events. The facility operates as a pooled insurance mechanism, enabling member countries to access rapid financial assistance for emergency response and recovery. This model not only ensures that countries can act quickly in the aftermath of disasters but also promotes the financial stability of nations, particularly those vulnerable to recurrent climate-induced hazards (World Bank, 2016). SEADRIF’s ability to provide timely funds has been lauded as a vital step in improving disaster preparedness and resilience in the region (Ratheesh, 2020).\nSimilarly, the ASEAN Disaster Risk Financing framework emphasizes the importance of regional cooperation in disaster risk reduction and management. By integrating financial instruments that support early disaster response and recovery, the framework aims to strengthen the financial capacities of its member states. This collaborative approach ensures that no country faces the financial burden of disaster response alone, fostering a sense of shared responsibility among ASEAN countries (ASEAN, 2020). The ASEAN framework’s focus on both risk reduction and financial preparedness complements SEADRIF’s immediate response model, offering a broader strategy for managing disaster risks across the region.\nTsunami Aftermath, 2009 15 Insurance and Risk Finance Mechanisms 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 These initiatives reflect the growing recognition of the need for collective action in addressing disaster-related financial risks. They represent a critical shift from traditional national-level disaster financing mechanisms to regional cooperation, enhancing resilience at a scale that individual countries could not achieve alone. Through pooled resources, joint risk management strategies, and innovative financial instruments, SEADRIF and ASEAN are setting important precedents for disaster risk financing in Southeast Asia.\nRegional risk financing initiatives, particularly through SEADRIF (Southeast Asia Disaster Risk Insurance Facility) and ASEAN’s framework continue to demonstrate several noteworthy successes in strengthening disaster resilience and providing timely financial support. One of the most significant achievements of SEADRIF has been its ability to offer insurance-based solutions that allow for the rapid disbursement of funds to member countries following disasters. This mechanism is critical in ensuring that immediate financial assistance is available to meet the urgent needs of affected communities. For instance, SEADRIF’s innovative parametric insurance model, which triggers payouts based on predefined criteria such as rainfall or wind speed thresholds, has proven effective in streamlining the financial response process, reducing administrative and bureaucratic delays, and increasing the speed of recovery (SEADRIF, 2021). This has been particularly important in countries with limited access to immediate post-disaster funding, as it provides a safety net that can be quickly mobilized.\nSimilarly, ASEAN’s broader collaborative framework on disaster risk financing has fostered a sense of solidarity and shared responsibility among its member nations. ASEAN’s approach, which encourages pooling of resources and expertise, has enhanced regional cooperation in managing disaster risks. This collaborative effort is especially vital in a region like Southeast Asia, where countries face common risks from typhoons, floods, earthquakes, and other natural hazards. ASEAN’s collective mechanisms, such as the ASEAN Agreement on Disaster Management and Emergency Response (AADMER), have facilitated coordinated responses to disasters, ensuring that resources are effectively mobilized across borders to assist the most affected nations (ASEAN, 2016).\nMoreover, the pooling of financial resources and risk management expertise has led to more effective regional preparedness. Through joint initiatives, member countries have been able to share knowledge and best practices, increasing their collective capacity to mitigate the impacts of disasters. This cooperation has been further strengthened by initiatives like the ASEAN Coordinating Centre for Humanitarian Assistance (AHA Centre), which serves as a central hub for coordinating disaster response efforts and resources (AHA Centre, 2023).\nThese regional initiatives have made notable strides in addressing the financial challenges posed by climate risks in the region. However, several challenges continue to delay their full effectiveness. One of the primary challenges is the uneven financial commitment and preparedness of participating countries. While some nations are able to make substantial contributions to the regional risk pool, others face difficulties in mobilizing the necessary resources. This disparity is often rooted in varying national economic capacities, political priorities, and levels of disaster vulnerability (Ariyananda, 2020).\n16 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 As a result, the regional pool’s effectiveness is hindered by insufficient contributions from certain countries, which impedes the capacity of the system to respond rapidly and effectively in times of need. This issue of financial commitment is compounded by the capacity limitations of some countries to implement risk financing strategies at the national level. For example, countries with less-developed financial infrastructure may find it challenging to align their local disaster management systems with regional frameworks (Tendler & Khalil, 2021).\nAnother significant obstacle is the complex coordination required among the diverse political systems and economies within the region. The heterogeneity of ASEAN member states, with varying levels of governance structures, financial systems, and disaster response capabilities, complicates the alignment of risk financing mechanisms. This fragmentation can lead to inefficiencies in the allocation and utilization of funds, as funds may not always be directed to the areas of greatest need or may be delayed due to bureaucratic hurdles (Chandani et al., 2020). Furthermore, the lack of standardized procedures across countries results in inconsistent implementation of risk financing strategies, diminishing their collective impact.\nThe experiences of the SEADRIF and ASEAN’s regional risk financing frameworks offer valuable lessons for Thailand as it seeks to enhance its own risk financing. These lessons highlight key opportunities for improvement, as well as the challenges that must be addressed in the development of a robust, comprehensive framework. One key lesson for Thailand is the successful implementation of insurance-based solutions within SEADRIF. SEADRIF’s use of insurance to provide rapid access to funds in the aftermath of disasters is a model that Thailand can adopt to ensure timely financial responses in the face of emergencies (Tendler & Khalil, 2021). By incorporating similar insurance mechanisms, Thailand can create a financial safety net that offers quick liquidity for immediate disaster response and recovery efforts. Moreover, such systems can help minimize the financial burden on the government and allow for faster recovery from catastrophic events, which is crucial given Thailand’s vulnerability to natural hazards such as floods, storms, and droughts (Chandani et al., 2020).\nAnother important lesson is the value of regional cooperation, as demonstrated by ASEAN’s risk financing framework. The collaborative approach within ASEAN facilitates the pooling of resources, sharing of best practices, and mutual support during emergencies. Thailand can benefit from strengthening its ties with neighboring countries to enhance disaster preparedness and response capabilities across borders (Ariyananda, 2020). In particular, regional cooperation can help address cross-border disasters and ensure a more cohesive regional response, which is particularly pertinent in Southeast Asia, where natural disasters often affect multiple countries simultaneously.\nThe experience of ASEAN also underscores the importance of addressing the challenges of resource mobilization and coordination. Thailand must ensure that its risk financing strategy is not only comprehensive but also practical in terms of engaging all relevant stakeholders. This includes ensuring active involvement from the government, the private sector, and local communities in the development, implementation, and funding of disaster risk financing mechanisms (Anderson et al., 2020). There is a strong need to establish clear roles and responsibilities for all stakeholders and develop mechanisms for effective coordination between different levels of government and sectoral actors. The challenges seen in ASEAN, where varying national priorities and financial capacities have sometimes hindered the smooth implementation of regional frameworks, highlight the need for careful planning and commitment at both the national and regional levels.\n17 Insurance and Risk Finance Mechanisms 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 17 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | 2024 Road Damage from Coastal Erosion Waves, 2023 18 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 THAILAND’S INSURANCE AND RISK FINANCING LANDSCAPE 04 Thailand is exposed to a wide range of climate-related risks. In particular, the country is highly susceptible to floods, with significant losses in recent years due to flood events. Due to its increased susceptibility to natural disasters like droughts, floods, and heavy rainfall, as well as the effects of sea level rise on the nation’s coastlines. Thailand is extremely vulnerable to the effects of climate change. Thailand was listed as the ninth most affected nation in terms of direct economic losses and human impacts from weather-related loss events from 2000 to 2019 by the Global Climate Risk Index 2021. In 2024, the southern part of Thailand experienced floods and flash floods due to the northeast monsoon’s heavy rainfall. According to DDPM Thailand, 136,219 households in the provinces of Satun, Surat Thani, Nakhon Si Thammarat, Songkhla, Pattani, Narathiwat, and Yala were impacted (DDPM, 2024). The total number of houses and schools affected by flood 2024 as per UNOSAT reports are 2,872 and 2 respectively.\nThailand, like many other nations, is grappling with the triple planetary crisis of climate change, pollution, and biodiversity loss. According to the 2021 Germanwatch Global Climate Risk Index, Thailand ranks as one of the ten countries most severely affected by flooding and stands ninth among the nations most impacted by weather-related loss events globally (UNDP 2023). The 2011 flood, which impacted over 13 million people, demonstrated the need for improved disaster risk financing mechanisms. Moreover, Thailand faces recurring droughts, with significant implications for its agriculture sector, a key part of the national economy. The government has recognized the urgent need to build resilience against these risks by implementing risk financing solutions, including insurance, and by improving its disaster management strategies (Nipon Poapongsakorn, 2017).\n19 Insurance and Risk Finance Mechanisms 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 Figure 1 Macro-perspective of insurance industry in Thailand Source: Country Diagnostic on Inclusive Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand, UNDP Over the previous five years, Thailand’s insurance market has grown somewhat. Since 2019, the life insurance industry, which accounts for 70% of the market based on gross premiums, has been gradually shrinking. Figure 1 indicates that the non-life insurance sector in Thailand expanded by 3.5% in 2020, despite the country’s GDP contracting by 6.2%. The rate of inflation, which raises insurance premiums, fluctuates in tandem with economic expansion. In 2020, the COVID-19 pandemic-induced recession resulted in deflation, or negative growth, of 0.8% during the same time frame. However, the price of insurance shouldn’t be significantly impacted by this brief deflation. In recent years, the Thai government has begun emphasizing the importance of integrating financial resilience into national and regional disaster management efforts. Thailand has increasingly focused on leveraging both traditional insurance and innovative financial tools to mitigate the impacts of disasters. Thailand’s insurance market, which includes both public and private insurance providers, is evolving with the aim of expanding coverage for climate risks, especially for vulnerable sectors such as agriculture and low-income populations. However, despite ongoing efforts, the penetration of insurance products related to natural disaster risks remains relatively low, especially in rural areas.\nThailand has comparatively lower insurance penetration rates and densities for both life and non-life businesses than the Asia-Pacific regional averages. Thailand’s insurance penetration rate in 2020 was significantly lower than the global average (Thailand 5.3% vs. global average 7.4%), particularly for non-life insurance (Thailand 1.9% vs. global average 4.1%). In a similar vein, Thailand’s insurance density was lower than the global average (383 USD versus 809 USD) as shown in figure 2.\n20 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 Figure 2 Life and Non-Life Insurance Penetration (%) from 2013-2020 Thailand has developed various frameworks and strategies aimed at enhancing its resilience to natural disasters and climate risks. One of the key components of these efforts is the National Disaster Risk Management Plan (NDRMP), which addresses ensuring effective responses to crises. The Thai government has been working on strategies to reduce financial risks through a mix of insurance, risk pools, and other financial instruments.\nIn 2016, Thailand, through the Office of the National Economic and Social Development Council (NESDC), introduced the Thailand Disaster Risk Management Framework (TDRMF). This strategy aims to improve the resilience of the country’s critical infrastructure and communities by ensuring that financial resources are available during emergencies. It includes mechanisms for risk financing, such as public-private partnerships (PPPs) and catastrophe bonds, though its implementation has faced challenges in terms of coordination and market readiness (UNDP, 2019).\nThe National Adaptation Plan (NAP) for climate change also plays an integral role in the country’s risk financing strategy. Under the NAP, Thailand has emphasized the need for innovative financing solutions to address the growing risks associated with climate change, particularly floods, droughts, and rising temperatures (Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment [MNRE], 2024).\nThailand’s approach to climate resilience is progressively integrating risk financing into national policies. The government’s Climate Change Master Plan (2015-2050) outlines the country’s long-term strategy for adapting to climate change, including measures for financing adaptation efforts. The plan proposes the establishment of a Climate Resilience Fund to support disaster management and climate change adaptation, ensuring that sufficient financial resources are available to address both immediate and long-term risks (Thailand’s Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment [MNRE], 2017).\nThe Thailand Greenhouse Gas Management Organization (TGO) also promotes strategies for addressing climate risks, which include financial instruments for mitigating climate impacts. Particularly, TGO focuses on mechanisms such as green bonds and sustainable financing tools to support climate resilience efforts (TGO, 2020). Moreover, disaster risk reduction (DRR) is integrated into the broader sustainable development agenda, aligning Thailand’s climate financing strategy with international frameworks like the Paris Agreement and the Sendai Framework for Disaster Risk 21 Thailand’s Insurance and Risk Financing Landscape 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 Reduction. These frameworks underscore the importance of financial instruments and strategies for managing and reducing climate-related risks (UNFCCC, 2015; UNDRR, 2015).\nThe Disaster Prevention and Mitigation Act B.E 2550 (2007) provides the legal foundation for disaster risk management in Thailand. This act established the National Disaster Prevention and Mitigation Committee (NDPMC), which oversees disaster risk management, including financing mechanisms. The Act emphasizes the need for risk financing solutions and mandates the creation of a contingency fund to support emergency responses. While the Act includes provisions for disaster relief, its focus on risk financing mechanisms and insurance is relatively limited (Office of the Prime Minister, 2007 and DDPM 2022). Further, the Flood and Storm Damage Compensation Act B.E. 2555 (2012) was introduced as part of the government’s efforts to provide financial relief to flood victims. This Act aimed to establish a system for compensating individuals and businesses affected by flood and storm disasters, reflecting the country’s growing awareness of the importance of financial protection against natural disasters (Oxfam, 2016).\nThailand’s Insurance Act B.E. 2535 (1992) is the cornerstone of the country’s insurance regulation. This Act provides a framework for the regulation of life and non-life insurance markets, which includes provisions for natural catastrophe insurance, although it has been criticized for limited penetration in disaster-related insurance products (Thai Insurance Regulatory Commission, 2017).\nThe Office of Insurance Commission (OIC), Thailand’s primary regulatory authority for the insurance industry, has introduced policies to promote the development of catastrophe insurance. However, the uptake of disaster-related insurance products remains limited, especially in rural areas. One of the key challenges in expanding disaster-related insurance in Thailand is the high cost of premiums and low consumer awareness (Insurance Regulatory Commission, 2017).\nThe Thai government has taken steps to address these challenges by promoting inclusive insurance initiatives, which aim to provide affordable insurance products to low-income households and vulnerable populations. These efforts have been supported by the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), which has collaborated with the Thai government to explore the development of low-cost insurance solutions for climate-related risks, especially for farmers in flood-prone regions (UNDP, 2020).\nThe UNDP’s Snapshot on Insurance and Risk Finance report provides an in-depth analysis of the current landscape of inclusive insurance and risk financing in Thailand. This report highlights critical insights into the country’s insurance market, revealing both the opportunities and challenges in expanding financial protection against disaster and climate-related risks. It underscores the importance of strengthening market readiness and enhancing insurance penetration to improve overall financial resilience (UNDP, 2023).\nThe Snapshot identifies several key issues, including coverage gaps and the limited adoption of inclusive insurance products, particularly among vulnerable communities such as smallholder farmers, low-income households, and informal workers. Despite Thailand’s progress in financial inclusion, the report notes that insurance coverage remains low, with significant gaps in areas prone to natural hazards. The analysis points out that the low uptake of insurance products can be attributed to a lack of awareness, limited product customization, and perceived high costs, 22 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 which deter potential policyholders (UNDP, 2023). Addressing these barriers is crucial for increasing coverage and building a more resilient financial system.\nThe report also examines the market readiness for risk financing solutions, such as parametric insurance and microinsurance. It highlights that while there is growing interest from the private sector and ongoing efforts by the government to support risk transfer mechanisms, the regulatory environment and financial infrastructure require further strengthening. The report emphasizes the need for enabling policies that foster innovation in insurance products and support public- private partnerships to scale up access to risk financing tools (UNDP, 2023).\nIn terms of ongoing initiatives, the UNDP’s Snapshot highlights various programs aimed at integrating insurance into broader risk financing strategies. For instance, the report mentions collaborative projects between the Thai government and international organizations, which focus on developing tailored insurance solutions for high-risk sectors, such as agriculture and small enterprises. These initiatives are aligned with Thailand’s National Financial Inclusion Strategy and the Climate Change Master Plan, reflecting a coordinated approach to building financial resilience (UNDP, 2023).\nOverall, the Snapshot report provides valuable insights into the current state of inclusive insurance and risk finance in Thailand. It identifies the critical role of data-driven approaches in designing effective insurance products, advocating for the use of advanced risk assessment tools and improved data collection methods. By addressing the existing market challenges and leveraging innovative financing solutions, Thailand can enhance its disaster preparedness and financial protection, reducing the economic impacts of climate and disaster risks.\n4.1. THAILAND INSURANCE MARKET Thailand’s insurance market has grown significantly over the past few decades, with both life and non-life sectors playing crucial roles in the economy. As of 2023, Thailand’s total insurance market size was valued at 918,067 million baht (approximately US$27 billion), with life insurance accounting for a significant share. Non-life insurance, which includes products related to natural disasters, represents about 31% of the market (OIC). The Office of Insurance Commission (OIC), the primary regulatory body for the Thai insurance market, is responsible for overseeing the market’s operations and ensuring that insurers comply with the relevant laws and regulations. Despite the growth of the market, disaster-related insurance penetration remains relatively low, particularly in rural and flood- prone areas (OIC, 2020). The key challenge in expanding insurance coverage is the high cost of premiums and limited consumer awareness regarding disaster insurance products.\nThailand’s catastrophe insurance market has seen gradual growth, driven in part by the country’s vulnerability to disasters such as floods, storms, and droughts. However, the development of catastrophe insurance has been slower than anticipated, due to factors like high premiums, poor understanding of the benefits, and the limited availability of specific coverage for natural disasters.\n23 Thailand’s Insurance and Risk Financing Landscape 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 In 2011, the devastating floods prompted a greater focus on catastrophe risk management. As a result, several public and private initiatives were launched to address the gap in disaster insurance coverage. For instance, the Flood Insurance Pool, established by the Thai government in collaboration with the insurance industry, aims to provide affordable insurance products for those most vulnerable to flooding, especially in flood-prone areas (Oxfam, 2017).\nDespite these efforts, the penetration of catastrophe insurance products remains limited, particularly among small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) and the agricultural sector. These sectors are highly vulnerable to climate-related risks but often lack the financial resources to afford comprehensive disaster insurance (UNDP, 2020).\nBetween 40.5% and 70% of MSMEs in ASEAN Member States ceased operations during the COVID-19 pandemic (ACCMSME, 2022). MSMEs lack adequate knowledge of and access to efficient coping strategies in the face of these growing risks. Less than 5% of MSMEs in the ASEAN region have insurance of any kind, and the majority of MSME financial solutions concentrate only on credit availability.\nThe needs of MSMEs are not met by traditional insurance products, and MSMEs have not been reached through suitable and creative distribution strategies. Agents and brokers, the main distribution channels for insurers, are not encouraged to reach MSMEs, and insurers frequently lack the data and information necessary to create suitable products. Additionally, insurers have found that MSMEs lack interest in or a thorough understanding of the benefits of insurance.\nThe Thai government has also implemented several government-backed insurance schemes to improve financial protection for low-income populations and vulnerable sectors. One key initiative is the Rice Farmer Insurance Program, which was introduced in 2015 to offer financial protection to farmers against natural disasters, such as floods and droughts, that affect agricultural yields. This program has been relatively successful in providing a safety net for farmers, but its effectiveness remains dependent on accurate risk assessments and timely payouts (United Nations, 2020).\nAdditionally, the government’s Flood Relief Fund and Storm Damage Compensation Fund offer financial assistance to individuals and businesses affected by major floods and storms. These funds provide compensation to cover the costs of rebuilding and recovery efforts. While these programs have played a critical role in post-disaster recovery, they are typically limited in their ability to fully address the long-term risks posed by recurrent disasters (UNDP, 2019).\nPublic-private partnerships (PPPs) have become an essential tool in disaster risk financing. The Thai government has explored various PPP models to enhance the capacity for disaster recovery and risk financing. These partnerships involve collaboration between government agencies and private sector insurers to create more effective, sustainable financial protection mechanisms.\n24 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 A notable example of PPPs in Thailand is the collaboration between the government and private insurers to create the National Catastrophe Insurance Pool (NCIP). The pool is designed to provide insurance coverage for both individuals and businesses in the event of a natural disaster, particularly floods. By pooling resources and sharing risks, the government aims to reduce the financial burden of disaster recovery while ensuring more widespread coverage (Asian Development Bank [ADB], 2016).\nAnother example of PPPs is the Thai Disaster Relief Fund, which has been supported by both the government and private insurers to provide immediate relief to those affected by large-scale disasters. This fund has been used to finance recovery efforts, but its sustainability remains an ongoing concern (World Bank, 2017).\n4.2. SOCIO-ECONOMIC FACTORS INFLUENCING INSURANCE DEMAND AND RISK FINANCING NEEDS Advancing work on insurance and insurance and risk financing in Thailand requires a nuanced understanding of the socio-economic and environmental factors that influence insurance demand and risk financing needs. These factors can significantly impact the country’s capacity to build resilience to climate-related risks and disasters. Understanding the complex dynamics between these factors is crucial to designing a comprehensive strategy that aligns with national priorities, addresses vulnerability, and fosters the broader goal of climate resilience.\nThis literature review assesses how various socio-economic and environmental factors can influence the demand for insurance and risk financing needs in Thailand, highlighting key trends and emerging issues that could affect the national strategy’s development.\nThe socio-economic landscape plays a pivotal role in shaping the demand for insurance products and the broader risk financing framework in Thailand. Key factors such as income levels, insurance literacy, access to financial services, and the informal economy all influence both the willingness to purchase insurance and the need for risk financing mechanisms.\n(i) Income Levels and Economic Inequality: Thailand’s economic structure is marked by significant disparities in income levels between urban and rural populations. According to a report by the World Bank (2020), while the country has seen economic growth, rural areas still face challenges related to poverty and lack of access to financial services. Lower-income households are less likely to afford insurance premiums, particularly for catastrophic risks such as floods or typhoons.\n(ii) Insurance Literacy and Awareness: Insurance literacy in Thailand remains relatively low, particularly in rural areas. Studies suggest that insurance products are often misunderstood, leading to a low adoption rate, especially for climate- related risks (Svensson, 2019). Improving awareness and understanding of insurance can play a significant role in boosting demand.\n(iii) Financial Inclusion: Access to formal financial products, including insurance, is a critical issue. The Bank of Thailand (2021) noted that despite growth in mobile banking and digital platforms, large segments of the population still rely on the informal sector for financial services, which hinders access to formal insurance products.\n25 Thailand’s Insurance and Risk Financing Landscape 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 (iv) Vulnerability of Informal Workers: The informal economy in Thailand is a significant factor affecting risk financing. A large proportion of the workforce, particularly in rural areas, is not covered by social insurance or formal risk financing mechanisms, which increases the need for government intervention and the development of inclusive, affordable insurance products (UNDP, 2023).\n(v) Digital Financial Services: The growing penetration of digital finance in Thailand, especially through mobile wallets and fintech, has the potential to increase access to micro-insurance products. Innovations such as parametric insurance via mobile platforms could reduce the cost of premiums and offer more inclusive coverage for low-income households (UNDP, 2023) (vi) Rising Middle Class: As Thailand’s middle class grows, there is increasing demand for more comprehensive and personalized insurance products. Urban populations are more likely to purchase property insurance, but the challenge remains to extend coverage to low-income and vulnerable groups.\n4.3. ENVIRONMENTAL FACTORS INFLUENCING INSURANCE DEMAND AND RISK FINANCING NEEDS Environmental factors, particularly climate change, are central to the growing demand for disaster risk financing in Thailand. The country is particularly vulnerable to typhoons, floods, droughts, and other climate-induced events, which increase the need for a robust insurance framework. Key environmental factors influencing risk financing needs are as follows: (i) Climate Change and Increasing Frequency of Extreme Events: Thailand is experiencing more frequent and intense climate events, particularly typhoons, flooding, and droughts. According to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC, 2021), Southeast Asia, including Thailand, is expected to face an increasing frequency of climate-related disasters, which intensifies the need for insurance and risk financing solutions.\n(ii) Agriculture Vulnerability: Agriculture, a major contributor to Thailand’s economy, is highly vulnerable to climate change. Farmers, especially in rural areas, face frequent losses due to flooding, droughts, and extreme weather patterns. Crop insurance has become a growing area of demand, yet many farmers still lack access to affordable insurance options. The World Bank (2019) reports that Thailand’s agricultural sector faces major barriers to effective risk financing, including high premiums and complex insurance terms that prevent wider adoption.\n(iii) Urbanization and Exposure to Risks: Thailand’s urban centers, particularly Bangkok, are increasingly exposed to flooding and storm surges due to rising sea levels and intense rainfall events. Urban resilience is becoming a priority, and the demand for property insurance and flood insurance is rising. However, there are challenges in aligning urban development with effective disaster risk management and insurance products that cater to urban residents.\n26 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 (iv) Natural Resource Depletion: Natural resource depletion, including water scarcity and land degradation, is driving the need for more sustainable risk financing solutions. The Thai government has begun to invest in green bonds and climate- adaptive insurance products to address the long-term challenges posed by environmental degradation and shifting agricultural patterns.\n(v) Climate Resilience and Green Insurance: There is growing interest in green insurance products that incentivize environmental sustainability while providing coverage for climate-related risks. Thailand could explore the integration of green bonds with disaster insurance products, encouraging private sector investment in climate-resilient infrastructure and green building insurance.\n(vi) Parametric Insurance for Climate Risks: The rise of parametric insurance, which provides payouts based on predefined environmental parameters (such as rainfall levels or wind speeds), is an emerging solution that could be scaled up in Thailand to address the growing risks from extreme weather and climate change.\n4.4. SOCIAL VULNERABILITY AND INSURANCE ACCESSIBILITY Thailand’s efforts to develop a national risk financing strategy must also consider the social vulnerability of certain populations. Social factors such as age, gender, and disability can significantly impact the ability to access and benefit from insurance products.\n(i) Vulnerable Populations: Poor households, particularly in rural areas, are often excluded from formal insurance markets due to low income, limited awareness, and lack of financial literacy. Women and the elderly, who are more likely to live in poverty, are particularly at risk of being excluded from climate risk insurance.\n(ii) Disaster Impact on Informal Sector Workers: Workers in the informal economy, such as day laborers, farmers, and small business owners, face greater risks from disasters and have less access to social safety nets or insurance products.\n(iii) Inclusive Insurance Products: Developing inclusive micro-insurance schemes tailored to low-income populations, including rural farmers, women, and elderly individuals, can address gaps in the current insurance coverage. Thailand could adopt models from countries like Sri Lanka and India, where community-based insurance and subsided premiums have been successful in increasing coverage among vulnerable groups.\n(iv) Public Asset Insurance: In addition to insuring individuals and businesses, Thailand’s financial resilience will benefit from public asset insurance. Public infrastructure, such as roads, schools, hospitals, and emergency services, plays a critical role in ensuring disaster resilience, particularly for vulnerable communities. When these assets are protected through insurance, it ensures faster recovery and continued provision of services to affected populations. For instance, if schools or health facilities are damaged in a disaster, their insurance can provide the funding needed for repairs, allowing them to reopen quickly and continue serving those in need.\n27 Thailand’s Insurance and Risk Financing Landscape 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 (v) Gender-Responsive Risk Financing: There is an emerging focus on gender- responsive disaster insurance and risk financing products. Women, particularly in rural areas, are disproportionately impacted by disasters. Including gender considerations in insurance policies can improve coverage and access for these groups.\n(vi) Economic Crisis and Affordability: The recent economic downturn, exacerbated by the COVID-19 pandemic, has made it harder for low-income households to afford insurance. This economic stress has led to a growing need for subsidized and affordable insurance products that address climate-related risks. To alleviate this challenge, Thailand can explore the introduction of credit insurance policies that would help businesses, especially small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) and low-income households, access affordable financing for disaster risk insurance. Credit insurance can provide protection to lenders against the risk of non-repayment due to disaster-related losses, thereby making it easier for vulnerable sectors to secure the necessary financial support to purchase insurance products. These policies can be structured to target specific sectors or communities most at risk, ensuring that insurance coverage becomes more accessible to those with limited financial capacity. Additionally, integrating subsidies or premium financing into these products will further enhance their affordability and increase uptake among the economically disadvantaged.\n(vii) Climate Change and Financial Risk: As climate risks increase, there is a need to enhance risk financing models and insurance mechanisms to ensure rapid disaster recovery while protecting vulnerable populations.\nUnderstanding the socio-economic and environmental factors that influence insurance demand and risk financing needs is critical for shaping an effective national strategy in Thailand. As climate change exacerbates risks, Thailand must adopt inclusive and innovative insurance solutions, addressing the needs of both urban and rural populations, while considering the unique vulnerabilities of women, farmers, and the informal workforce. Moreover, integrating digital solutions and green insurance products can significantly improve financial inclusion and resilience to climate risks.\nWoman Wearing PM2.5 Mask, 2024 28 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 4.5. KEY GAPS IN CURRENT MECHANISMS While Thailand has made progress in developing insurance and risk financing mechanisms, several gaps remain that need to be addressed for a more comprehensive, inclusive, and sustainable system. These gaps include: (i) Low Insurance Penetration One of the main challenges in Thailand’s disaster risk financing system is the low penetration of insurance products, particularly for low-income households, small businesses, and rural populations who are most vulnerable to natural disasters. According to a study by UNDP (2020), less than 5% of the population in flood-prone areas of Thailand has access to flood insurance. The high cost of premiums, limited knowledge of insurance benefits, and lack of trust in the insurance system are major barriers to increasing insurance uptake.\n(ii) Insufficient Coverage for Emerging Risks Thailand’s insurance market, particularly for climate risks and disasters, remains focused on traditional risks, such as floods and storms. However, emerging climate risks, such as heatwaves, extreme droughts, and changing agricultural patterns due to climate change, are not adequately covered by existing insurance products. The Thai government and insurance companies need to develop more tailored products that can cover these evolving risks.\nFor example, insurance for climate-induced migration or coverage for drought-related crop losses is currently not available, even though such risks are increasingly important for rural farmers and communities dependent on agriculture (Asian Development Bank, 2020). The lack of innovative risk products that respond to these emerging challenges means that significant risks remain uninsured.\n(iii) Limited Synergies between Climate Change Adaptation and Risk Financing Risk financing measures have not yet been integrated into climate change adaptation (CCA) and disaster risk reduction (DRR) policy frameworks. Similarly, CCA and DRR principles are not yet fully integrated into risk financing approaches. While there is a recognition of the importance of disaster risk financing in the face of climate change, current policies lack a comprehensive approach to integrating climate adaptation measures with risk financing. For example, while Thailand has a National Adaptation Plan (NAP), the synergy between disaster risk financing mechanisms and adaptation strategies remains weak (UNDP, 2020).\nThe Green Climate Fund (GCF) and Adaptation Fund (AF) have provided funding for climate resilience initiatives, but more focused efforts are needed to ensure that these funds are channeled into scalable and accessible insurance and risk financing solutions for vulnerable communities (GCF, 2019).\n29 Thailand’s Insurance and Risk Financing Landscape 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 (iv) Fragmented Risk Financing Frameworks Risk financing mechanisms in Thailand are often fragmented, with different government agencies and private insurers offering separate and sometimes uncoordinated schemes. For instance, the Flood Relief Fund and Catastrophe Insurance Pool operate independently, with limited coordination on risk assessment, funding mechanisms, and payout systems. This fragmentation results in inefficiencies and gaps in the coverage, especially during large-scale or multi-hazard events.\nThe lack of coordination between these mechanisms means that, during a disaster, affected individuals may face delays in receiving financial support, or they may not be covered under certain schemes, which undermines the effectiveness of the overall risk financing system.\n(v) Lack of Awareness and Capacity Building Despite various government-backed programs, there remains a significant gap in awareness and capacity building for disaster insurance and risk financing among key stakeholders, including local communities, insurers, and even government officials. Limited public understanding of the value of disaster risk insurance products contributes to the low demand for these products. Similarly, insurers often lack the necessary data and risk modeling capacity to design appropriate products for emerging risks (World Bank, 2017).\n4.6. OPPORTUNITIES FOR STRENGTHENING INSURANCE AND RISK FINANCING IN THAILAND There are several opportunities for strengthening Thailand’s disaster insurance and risk financing systems. These opportunities include addressing existing gaps, improving accessibility and affordability of insurance products, and integrating climate change resilience into national policies and frameworks.\n(i) Expanding Catastrophe Insurance and Risk Pools One key opportunity is to expand and enhance Thailand’s catastrophe insurance schemes, particularly the Flood Insurance Pool, by ensuring better accessibility, affordability, and coverage for vulnerable populations. This could involve subsidizing premiums for low-income households and small businesses in high-risk areas to encourage higher uptake of insurance products. In addition, expanding the pool to cover a wider range of risks, including earthquakes, droughts, and extreme heatwaves, would increase its relevance as a tool for risk financing.\nMoreover, the government could work with the private sector to create multi-hazard insurance products that cover a range of risks, from floods to droughts, which would make the products more appealing to a broader audience (ADB, 2020).\n30 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 (ii) Integrating Climate Change Adaptation into Risk Financing Given Thailand’s vulnerability to climate change, integrating climate change adaptation strategies into the national disaster risk financing framework offers a significant opportunity. This could involve incorporating climate risks into risk assessments and insurance models, ensuring that the risks associated with temperature changes, droughts, and shifting agricultural patterns are adequately covered.\nTo achieve this, Thailand could work with international organizations such as the UNDP and World Bank to develop innovative financing mechanisms, such as climate bonds or insurance-linked securities, that channel investments into resilience-building projects and adaptation measures for vulnerable populations (UNFCCC, 2020).\n(iii) Strengthening Public-Private Partnerships (PPPs) Expanding public-private partnerships (PPPs) in the insurance and disaster risk financing space presents another opportunity. Thailand’s existing National Catastrophe Insurance Pool (NCIP) could be strengthened through better collaboration between the government and private insurers, ensuring that sufficient capital is available to cover larger-scale events.\nThe government could also explore opportunities for risk-sharing agreements with international reinsurance markets to spread the financial risk of catastrophic events. Additionally, Thailand could work with private insurers to improve disaster risk modeling and early warning systems, allowing for more accurate pricing and coverage for climate and disaster risks (World Bank, 2017).\n(iv) Capacity Building and Awareness Raising A key opportunity to enhance the effectiveness of Thailand’s risk financing system is through capacity building and awareness-raising efforts aimed at both the public and private sectors. This includes enhancing financial literacy about disaster risk insurance and integrating disaster risk financing into school curriculums, government training programs, and public campaigns. Additionally, there is a crucial need to ensure that insurance products and risk financing mechanisms are gender-responsive and designed with a Leave No One Behind (LNOB) approach, particularly for vulnerable and marginalized groups, including women, rural populations, and low-income households. Efforts should focus on tailoring products that meet the specific needs of women, such as providing coverage for health emergencies, family losses, and livelihoods. Moreover, integrating these aspects into awareness campaigns will help ensure that these populations are not excluded from climate and disaster risk financing solutions. Building the capacity of insurers to understand the gendered impacts of disasters and climate change, as well as developing inclusive policies that address the specific vulnerabilities of women and marginalized groups, is essential. By prioritizing gender equality and inclusivity in risk financing, Thailand can foster greater resilience in all sectors of society. For insurers, it would be beneficial to invest in building the capacity to use more sophisticated tools for risk assessment, including remote sensing data and climate forecasting technologies (UNDP, 2020).\n31 Thailand’s Insurance and Risk Financing Landscape 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 (v) Digital Solutions for Financial Inclusion The growing penetration of mobile technology and digital financial platforms in Thailand offers an opportunity to expand access to insurance products. Mobile phone-based disaster insurance products and digital platforms for micro-insurance could help reach the most vulnerable populations, particularly in rural and flood-prone areas (ADB, 2020). Similarly, the use of satellite data, which provides enormous efficiency for implementing parametric and index-based insurances. Leveraging technology for data collection, risk mapping, and early warning systems would improve the efficiency and accuracy of insurance payouts, helping to better serve those most in need.\nFlooded Lat Prao Intersection, 2012 32 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 STRATEGIC INTERVENTIONS AND INITIATIVES 05 To effectively advance insurance and risk financing in Thailand, a series of strategic actions and initiatives are required under the roadmap. The roadmap outlines a number of strategic actions that are aimed at advancing Thailand’s insurance and risk financing landscape, with an emphasis on inclusivity, innovation, and resilience to climate change. These actions not only address Thailand’s specific needs but also leverage lessons from successful models in other countries. Drawing lessons from countries like Mexico, the Philippines, India, and Kenya, these initiatives can strengthen Thailand’s capacity to manage risks and provide financial protection to its citizens, particularly vulnerable groups. By combining comprehensive risk assessment, public-private partnerships, innovative financing, and strong institutional frameworks, Thailand can build a sustainable and scalable insurance and risk finance system.\nFollowing are the six key strategic interventions identified under this roadmap: 33 Strategic Interventions and Initiatives 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 5.1. DEVELOPMENT OF A NATIONAL STRATEGY / FRAMEWORK As a first step under the roadmap, a national strategy / framework needs to be developed, which in addition to identifying potential instruments also clearly defines the roles and responsibilities of each stakeholder. To further expedite the effective development and implementation of the strategy, a technical working group or task force could be established, which would be composed of representatives from key government departments and ministries, insurance industry, and international organizations. Likewise, there is a need to develop a comprehensive regulatory framework that integrates risk finance with the insurance sector. This should ensure clear roles for the public and private sectors, with an emphasis on affordability, accessibility, and climate resilience. Thailand can learn from Mexico that has issued catastrophe bonds to provide financial liquidity in the event of natural disasters. The country uses these bonds as part of its larger risk financing strategy, which is a blend of public funding, international financing, and private insurance mechanisms. Likewise, the Philippines has established a strong regulatory framework that combines public financing and private insurance to address natural disaster risks, offering a model for institutionalizing disaster risk management and financing.\n5.2. ESTABLISHMENT OF COMPREHENSIVE RISK ANALYTICS Another main area of intervention identified under the roadmap is the establishment of comprehensive data and risk assessment systems. This could be done by establishing a centralized national database that incorporates climate and disaster risk data, geospatial data, and historical disaster data. Putting in place comprehensive risk analytics will aid in better forecasting, risk modeling, and pricing of insurance products.\nIncreasing investments in the development of actuarial capacity can also be coupled with overall risk analytics in subsequent phase. This would allow insurers to accurately assess the risks associated with disasters and climate change, and to develop appropriate pricing structures for insurance policies. Strong collaborations with international organizations (e.g., the World Bank, UNDP, ADB) and national meteorological agencies to develop high-quality climate risk data and ensure its integration into national risk models and insurance schemes would prove beneficial. Several countries have invested in developing such models and are able to reduce risk as a direct consequence.\n5.3. DEVELOPMENT OF INCLUSIVE INSURANCE PRODUCTS One of the most significant intervention areas is the designing and development of inclusive insurance products under this roadmap. It is significant to introduce parametric insurance products that can provide quick payouts based on measurable triggers (e.g., wind speed for hurricanes, rainfall levels for floods). These products are particularly effective in managing climate-related risks and are easier to implement in developing economies.\nAdditionally, the promotion of microinsurance products that cater to low-income groups, such as smallholder farmers, and weather-based insurance schemes that protect them from crop failure due to changing climatic conditions is needed through the country. Numerous countries have already developed and successfully implemented such instruments from who 34 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 Thailand can learn. For instance, Kenya has a successful model for providing microinsurance to low-income individuals, particularly in rural areas. By partnering with mobile phone networks, Kenya has significantly expanded access to affordable insurance products. Likewise, India has implemented weather-based crop insurance schemes that automatically trigger payouts based on changes in weather conditions, helping small farmers recover from losses caused by droughts or floods.\nIn addition to parametric and microinsurance products, it is essential to design gender-responsive insurance products that address the specific needs and vulnerabilities of women, especially in rural and disaster-prone areas. Women often face greater barriers to accessing financial services, including insurance, due to socio-cultural norms, limited access to education, and lower levels of financial literacy. Developing insurance products that are tailored to the unique challenges women face—such as those that provide support in the event of family loss, livelihood disruption, or medical emergencies—will empower women and promote financial inclusion. Furthermore, gender-responsive products should consider women’s roles in agriculture and disaster response, ensuring that they are adequately protected against climate-related risks. By addressing gender disparities in insurance access and coverage, Thailand can ensure more equitable and inclusive disaster risk financing.\n5.4. STRENGTHENING PUBLIC-PRIVATE PARTNERSHIPS (PPP) It is evident that to ensure sustainability and wide coverage of the instruments, establishing and strengthening public-private partnerships (PPP) to share the financial burden of climate-related risks is required. This could include co-financing insurance premiums for vulnerable populations or providing subsidies to make insurance more affordable for farmers and small businesses.\nPublic Private Partnerships can help pool resources from both public and private sectors and such funds can be used to provide immediate financial relief in the aftermath of major disasters while being replenished through insurance mechanisms. Costa Rica has a successful model of risk sharing, where the government partners with private insurers to offer a national disaster risk insurance scheme. This allows the government to access rapid financial resources while providing affordable insurance for the public. Likewise, Colombia established a National Disaster Risk Management Fund that combines contributions from the public sector, private insurers, and international donors to ensure that adequate financial resources are available for disaster recovery.\n5.5. INSTITUTIONAL STRENGTHENING AND MARKET DEVELOPMENT Building the capacity of local insurance providers, brokers, and regulators to handle climate and disaster risk insurance products is of great significance for mainstreaming insurance and risk financing. This involves training in risk assessment, underwriting, claims management, and reinsurance strategies. Similarly, enhancing the capacity of key stakeholders, for instance Department of Disaster Prevention and Mitigation (DDPM), Ministry of Finance, National Economic and Social Development Council (NESDC), and Department of Local Administration and other relevant departments at the provincial levels to coordinate with the insurance sector and manage risk financing effectively could prove the key to success. This could be facilitated by the creation of risk financing units within government ministries.\n35 Strategic Interventions and Initiatives 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 In parallel strengthening regulatory capacity with the help of Office of Insurance Commission (OIC) to oversee the development and implementation of climate and disaster risk insurance, ensuring transparency, equity, and financial stability within the insurance market. In addition, the Insurance Association of Thailand and other industry stakeholders, such as brokers, reinsurers, and financial institutions, must be actively engaged in the policy-making process.\nSouth Africa has a well-developed insurance regulatory body that oversees all aspects of insurance, including climate and disaster risk coverage. Their framework could serve as a model for Thailand to ensure effective governance in the insurance sector. Likewise, Pakistan’s NDRMF has successfully built capacity to manage disaster risk financing in a coordinated manner. The NDRMF model involves partnerships between government and private sector entities and is an example of institutional strengthening.\n5.6. DEVELOPMENT OF INNOVATIVE FINANCING INSTRUMENTS The roadmap identifies exploring and developing innovative financial instruments as one of the intervention areas, e.g., the use of catastrophe bonds and climate bonds as mechanisms to raise funds for disaster response. These bonds could be issued by the government or private entities to provide liquidity in times of major climate events, with repayments linked to the occurrence of specified natural disasters. Likewise, parametric instruments could be exclusively developed to provide protection to the public asset.\nThis roadmap also suggests creating or joining a sovereign risk pool with other countries in the region to share risks associated with climate-related disasters, e.g., SEADRIF. This could reduce the financial burden on Thailand and enhance regional cooperation in managing climate risks.\nThere are quite a few examples around the world to understand the risk pool advantages and benefits. There are risk pools in the Caribbean region, as well as for the Pacific countries. These pools allow the member countries to collectively share the financial risks of natural disasters. World Bank has facilitated catastrophe bond issuances for several governments to raise capital for disaster relief. These instruments could be considered by Thailand as part of a broader insurance and risk finance strategy.\n36 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 PHASED APPROACH OF ROADMAP 06 The roadmap for developing a national strategy on insurance and risk financing in Thailand aims to establish a clear and structured approach to integrating insurance and risk financing solutions into the country’s broader disaster risk management framework. It is designed to facilitate the identification, assessment, and management of risks, while also promoting financial inclusion and market development for insurance.\nThe roadmap follows a phased approach to ensure that foundational elements are in place before advancing to more complex levels of strategy development and implementation. The roadmap is divided into three main phases, i.e., Foundation, Development, and Consolidation. Each phase is aligned with specific objectives and targets that address short, medium, and long-term goals.\n37 Phased Approach of Roadmap 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 6.1. PHASE 1: FOUNDATION (2024 - 2025) The purpose of the Phase 1 is to provide solid anchorage and establish the foundational legal, regulatory, and institutional frameworks for insurance and risk finance in Thailand via the roadmap. Building upon a comprehensive review of existing legal and regulatory the roadmap will help identify gaps, overlaps, and opportunities for incorporating insurance and risk financing solutions into the current framework. Simultaneously, the stakeholder engagements and consultations with key government and other stakeholders will gather inputs on the needs and priorities for insurance integration into disaster risk management. Post roadmap development, the work will further build upon the diagnostic study conducted by UNDP and IRFF by expanding capacity-building initiatives to key stakeholders on the concepts of risk finance and inclusive insurance. This phase will also include capacity development workshops with regulators and insurers on innovative insurance products such as parametric insurance and catastrophe bonds. Consequently, a futuristic National Disaster Risk Finance Strategy will provide tangible anchorage in the policy, legal and regulatory environment in the context of insurance and risk finance in Thailand and legal comprehensive assessment report on the existing legal and policy environment for risk finance and insurance, alongside capacity development programs for key stakeholders.\n6.2. PHASE 2: DEVELOPMENT (2025 - 2027) The Phase 2 of the roadmap targeting short to medium term, would lead to the initiation of the development of key insurance products, mechanisms, and pilot projects in priority regions.\nThe development phase will mainly see the development of the Thailand’s National Strategy on Insurance and Risk Finance and will see it clubbed with prioritization of inclusive insurance products tailored to the needs of vulnerable populations, such as microinsurance and parametric insurance. The development of sovereign risk financing instruments, such as catastrophe bonds or insurance-linked securities, and interventions supporting public asset insurance will also be explored and deliberated to assess the feasibility of each instrument. This will also be coupled with the launch of pilot projects in high-risk areas of Thailand, targeting regions prone to flooding, droughts, and other climate risks. These pilots will test the effectiveness of newly developed insurance products and their alignment with Thailand’s national development goals.\nDuring the development phase, the foundation phase will further be strengthened as the regulatory environment for inclusive insurance by working with the OIC to introduce reforms that support the scalability of new insurance products will be carried forward further. This could include incentives for insurers to develop inclusive products and simplified insurance procedures for low-income populations.\n38 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 6.3. PHASE 3: CONSOLIDATION (2025 - 2030) The consolidation phase of the roadmap will see the integration of inclusive insurance and risk financing solutions into Thailand’s long-term national development and disaster risk management strategies. Building upon the lessons learned from the previous phases, this phase will focus on the implementation of Thailand’s first comprehensive National Strategy on Insurance and Risk Finance. This strategy will be aligned with Thailand’s Nationally Determined Contributions (NDCs) and other global frameworks, such as the Sendai Framework for Disaster Risk Reduction and the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). The consolidation phase will also prioritize institutionalization by working with government agencies to internalize inclusive insurance solutions within existing disaster risk management processes, ensuring sustainability and scalability and will help establish permanent institutional mechanisms, such as a national risk financing task force, to oversee the implementation of the national strategy. The most significant component of the consolidation phase will be the development and implementation of a robust M&E framework to track the progress and impact of not only the strategy, but each rolled out and piloted instrument. This will involve setting clear metrics and indicators for measuring success in terms of insurance penetration rates, reduction in economic losses from disasters, and enhanced resilience of vulnerable communities.\nThe Sinking House, 2013 39 Phased Approach of Roadmap 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 PHASE ACTIONS / TARGETS TIME SCALE PHASE – I: Foundation (2024 - 25) i. Establish National Risk Financing Framework: • Form the National Risk Financing Task Force composed of key stakeholders (government, private insurers, academia, and international partners).\n• Conduct the literature review and stakeholder consultations to identify gaps in insurance and risk financing.\n• Develop an initial policy framework for risk financing, with a focus on climate and disaster risks.\nSHORT TERM (1 - 2 Years) ii. Identify Pilot Insurance Schemes: • Identify pilot weather-based and parametric insurance products for smallholder farmers, rural communities, and other vulnerable sectors, e.g., public assets.\n• Target initial microinsurance initiatives in flood-prone or high-risk agricultural areas to test insurance uptake and effectiveness.\niii. Public Awareness and Education Campaign: • Conduct public awareness campaigns to educate communities, businesses, and government officials about the importance of insurance and risk financing.\n• Engage local media and community leaders to promote the benefits of disaster insurance and climate risk adaptation.\niv. Develop Disaster Risk Data Infrastructure: • Start creating a disaster risk database to gather data on climate risks, natural disasters, and socioeconomic vulnerabilities.\n• Collect national-level data on climate risks and begin the process of integrating disaster risk data from various sectors (e.g., agriculture, infrastructure, health).\nv. Initial Institutional Strengthening: • Begin training programs for local insurers, actuaries, and risk assessors to develop expertise in climate-related risks and insurance products.\n• Begin to strengthen the capacity of the Insurance Regulatory Authority (IRA) to regulate and oversee climate risk insurance products.\n40 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 PHASE ACTIONS / TARGETS TIME SCALE PHASE – II: Development (2025 - 27) i. Develop and Launch the National Risk Financing Strategy: • Finalize and launch the National Risk Financing Strategy, which outlines the government’s approach to integrating insurance products, risk financing mechanisms, and disaster management into one cohesive framework.\n• Establish clear roles and responsibilities for all stakeholders, including public, private, and community entities, in managing climate risks.\nMEDIUM TERM (3 - 5 Years) ii. Establish National Disaster Risk Fund (NDRF): • Launch the National Disaster Risk Fund (NDRF), with contributions from both public and private sectors.\n• Define clear operational guidelines for how the NDRF will operate, particularly during major disaster events, ensuring quick access to funds for recovery efforts.\niii. Identify Pilot Insurance Schemes: • Roll out pilot weather-based and parametric insurance products for smallholder farmers, rural communities, and other vulnerable sectors.\n• Target initial microinsurance initiatives in flood-prone or high-risk agricultural areas to test insurance uptake and effectiveness.\niv. Scale Up Insurance Product Accessibility: • Expand weather-based insurance and parametric insurance offerings to include more sectors, including infrastructure and small businesses in high-risk areas.\n• Scale microinsurance products to cover a larger portion of the rural population and informal sector workers.\n• Begin to integrate climate risk considerations into insurance product designs, especially for agriculture, health, and housing sectors.\n41 Phased Approach of Roadmap 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 PHASE ACTIONS / TARGETS TIME SCALE PHASE – II: Development (2025 - 27) v. Strengthen Public-Private Risk Sharing Mechanisms: • Build partnerships for public-private risk-sharing schemes, where the government and insurers share the financial responsibility for disaster risks, creating a more sustainable financing model.\n• Develop regional partnerships with neighboring Southeast Asian countries to create cross-border risk pools, allowing for more effective risk-sharing in the region.\nMEDIUM TERM (3 - 5 Years) vi. Enhanced Institutional and Regulatory Capacity: • Develop and implement training programs for insurers, regulators, and disaster risk management professionals on climate risks, parametric insurance, and risk financing solutions.\n• Establish mechanisms for effective monitoring and evaluation of insurance market performance, including insurance penetration and claims processes.\n• Strengthen the regulatory framework for risk financing, ensuring that insurers comply with national standards and global best practices.\nPHASE ACTIONS / TARGETS TIME SCALE PHASE – III: Consolidation (2025 - 35) i. Achieve Widespread Insurance Coverage: • Ensure that insurance coverage is widespread, with a focus on high-risk sectors, including agriculture, housing, and businesses in disaster-prone regions.\n• Aim for at least 50% penetration of weather-based insurance across agricultural regions and other vulnerable sectors.\n• Expand inclusive insurance products to include all socioeconomic groups, particularly vulnerable populations in rural and informal sectors.\nLONG TERM (5 - 10 Years) 42 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 PHASE ACTIONS / TARGETS TIME SCALE PHASE – III: Consolidation (2025 - 35) ii. Full Integration of Climate Risks into Insurance and Risk Financing: • Fully integrate climate change adaptation strategies into the national insurance and risk financing strategy, ensuring that insurance solutions evolve in response to changing climate patterns.\n• Use advanced risk modeling to better understand future climate risks, adjusting insurance products accordingly to cover emerging risks such as sea-level rise, extreme weather events, and shifting agricultural patterns.\nLONG TERM (5 - 10 Years) iii. Regional and International Risk Pool Participation • Join regional risk pools such as the Asian Risk Pool or ASEAN catastrophe risk pool to further diversify risks and reduce the financial burden on Thailand in the event of large-scale disasters.\n• Develop cross-border insurance products that address regional risks, particularly for climate-related events, to facilitate more efficient and cost-effective risk financing solutions.\niv. Strengthen Financial Sustainability of Disaster Risk Financing Mechanisms: • Secure sustainable financing mechanisms for disaster response, ensuring that the National Disaster Risk Fund (NDRF) remains capitalized and operational over the long term.\n• Explore and issue catastrophe bonds or other innovative financial products to further strengthen Thailand’s financial resilience to climate risks and disasters.\nv. Global Leadership in Disaster Risk Finance: • Position Thailand as a regional leader in climate risk financing, with the country offering best practices and solutions for integrating insurance and risk finance into disaster management and climate adaptation.\n• Expand collaborations with international financial institutions such as the World Bank, UNDP, and other regional organizations to share knowledge and resources in the field of climate risk financing.\n43 Phased Approach of Roadmap 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 MONITORING AND EVALUATION (M&E) FRAMEWORK FOR THE ROADMAP 07 Success of the roadmap on Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand is strongly linked with a robust Monitoring and Evaluation (M&E) framework to track progress, evaluate the effectiveness of initiatives, and ensure timely adjustments to meet long-term goals. The M&E plan will focus on the collection of baseline data, tracking of Key Performance Indicators (KPIs), and the regular review of progress across short, medium, and long-term targets. Below is a detailed M&E framework for this roadmap: 44 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 7.1. BASELINE DATA COLLECTION a) Actions: The purpose of undertaking the baseline data collection is to establish a reference point for measuring progress and assess the current state of insurance penetration, disaster risk financing, and regulatory frameworks.\n(i) Insurance Penetration: Collect data on the current state of insurance coveragein key sectors (e.g., agriculture, health, infrastructure). This will involve working with the Insurance Regulatory Authority (IRA), insurance companies, and the Ministry of Finance to obtain data on the number of policies issued, claims paid, and sectoral coverage.\n(ii) Disaster Risk Financing Mechanisms: Assess the existing disaster risk financing tools and mechanisms (e.g., contingency funds, catastrophe bonds) used in Thailand. Collect data on their use, effectiveness, and accessibility.\n(iii) Regulatory Framework: Review the current legal and regulatory environment for insurance products, focusing on policies that support climate-related insurance products and disaster risk financing.\nb) Target Timeline: (i) Short-term (0 - 6 months): Data collection and assessment of current insurance coverage, disaster risk financing mechanisms, and regulatory frameworks.\n7.2. KEY PERFORMANCE INDICATORS (KPIs) a) Actions: KPIs need to be developed and tracked in order to assess progress in key areas of the roadmap, e.g., insurance penetration, regulatory improvements, and disaster risk reduction. The following shows a representative set of indicators that could be used to measure the progress on insurance and risk finance. (i) Insurance Penetration KPIs • Target: Increase in the number of insurance policies issued in vulnerable sectors (e.g., agriculture, microinsurance, flood insurance).\n• Indicator: Year-on-year increase in the number of policies in high-risk areas.\n(ii) Regulatory Enhancement KPIs: • Target: Improvement in the regulatory environment for climate-related insurance products.\n• Indicator: Number of new regulations or amendments to existing laws that support climate risk financing, parametric insurance, and microinsurance.\n(iii) Disaster Risk Reduction KPIs: • Target: Reduction in financial losses due to climate and disaster-related risks.\n• Indicator: Decrease in uninsured losses and out-of-pocket expenses for households and businesses after disasters.\n45 Monitoring and Evaluation (M&E) Framework for the Roadmap 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 (iv) Insurance Market Performance KPIs: • Target: Growth in the insurance sector’s ability to meet disaster risk and climate-related demands.\n• Indicator: Increased number of products developed and available to consumers (e.g., parametric insurance, agricultural insurance).\nb) Target Timeline: (i) Short-term (0 - 6 months): Establishment and validation of KPIs based on baseline data.\n(ii) Medium-term (1 - 3 years): Continuous monitoring and refinement of KPIs.\n(iii) Long-term (5 - 10 years): Full integration of KPIs into national insurance and risk finance policy.\n7.3. SEMI-ANNUAL OR ANNUAL REVIEW a) Actions: It is highly significant to conduct regular reviews of the roadmap’s progress to ensure it remains aligned with national priorities, and to identify areas requiring adjustments.\n(i) Semi / Annual Review Process: • Hold semi-annual meetings involving key stakeholders (government ministries, insurance companies, civil society) to assess the progress of the roadmap and identify challenges.\n• Evaluate whether short-term and medium-term targets are being met, and discuss any emerging trends or challenges.\n• Share findings with the public and stakeholders through progress reports and transparency platforms.\n(ii) Annual Reports: • Develop an annual progress report documenting achievements, challenges, and recommendations for the next year.\n• Ensure the report includes both quantitative data (e.g., insurance penetration) and qualitative assessments (e.g., stakeholder engagement, policy reforms).\nb) Target Timeline: (i) Short-term (0 - 2 years): Semi-annual and annual review meetings, with reports and adjustments.\n(ii) Medium-term (3 - 5 years): Annual review focusing on evaluating the outcomes of pilot projects and policy reforms.\n(iii) Long-term (5 - 10 years): Long-term evaluation of the roadmap’s impact on national insurance coverage, risk reduction, and financial resilience.\n46 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 7.4. MID-TERM EVALUATION a) Actions: The proposed M&E framework also advises conducting a comprehensive evaluation at the end of Phase 2 (Medium-Term), assessing the effectiveness and overall impact of the pilot projects, regulatory reforms, and stakeholder engagement.\n(i) Mid-Term Evaluation Process: • Evaluate the impact of pilot projects (e.g., parametric insurance, microinsurance, disaster risk financing mechanisms) on vulnerable populations, including the financial resilience of targeted sectors.\n• Assess whether regulatory reforms have enabled the growth of climate risk-related insurance products.\n• Gather feedback from key stakeholders about the feasibility and effectiveness of ongoing programs.\n• Measure the effectiveness of data collection efforts and risk assessments in informing decision-making.\n(ii) Mid-Term Evaluation Report: • Develop a mid-term evaluation report with specific recommendations for adjustments to the strategy.\n• Focus on areas such as the scalability of pilot projects, effectiveness of stakeholder engagement, and regulatory gaps.\nb) Target Timeline: (i) Medium-term (3 - 5 years): Complete a mid-term evaluation and adjust the roadmap based on findings.\n7.5. LONG-TERM IMPACT ASSESSMENT a) Actions: It is also of high significant that to assess the long-term impact of the roadmap in achieving the overall objectives, including increased insurance penetration, enhanced disaster risk financing, and a stronger regulatory framework, long-term impact assessment is undertaken. (i) Long-Term Evaluation Process: • Conduct a comprehensive evaluation at the end of the 10-year period, assessing the overall success of the national strategy on insurance and risk finance.\n• Evaluate whether the strategy has improved Thailand’s financial resilience against climate-related risks and disasters, and whether new insurance products have been successfully integrated into the market.\n• Assess the long-term sustainability of the insurance market in meeting the needs of vulnerable populations.\n47 Monitoring and Evaluation (M&E) Framework for the Roadmap 01 | 02 | 03 | 04 | 05 | 06 | 07 | 08 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 (ii) Long-Term Impact Report: • Develop a long-term impact report that outlines successes, challenges, and lessons learned over the course of the strategy’s implementation.\n• Use the findings to inform future updates to the national strategy, ensuring continued progress toward climate resilience.\nb) Target Timeline: (i) Long-term (5 - 10 years): Final evaluation and long-term impact report.\nFlooded Toll Booth on the Expressway in Bangkok, 2011 48 Insurance and Risk Finance for Thailand: A Roadmap | December 2024 REFERENCES 08 • AHA Centre. (2023). Regional Cooperation and Disaster Response. ASEAN Coordinating Centre for Humanitarian Assistance. Retrieved from www.ahacentre.org • Allianz. (2022). Emerging Climate Risks and Insurance Market Trends in Asia. Munich: Allianz SE.\n• Anderson, M., Elliott, G., & Tan, R. (2020). Data gaps and disaster risk financing: Challenges in Southeast Asia. Journal of Climate Risk and Financing, 14(3), 110-125.\n• Ariyananda, P. (2020). Finan